```javascript
app.directive('stSelectAll', function() {
	return {
		restrict: 'E',
		template: '<input type="checkbox" ng-model="isAllSelected" />',
		scope: {
			all: '='
		},
		link: function(scope, element, attr) {
			scope.$watch('isAllSelected', function() {
				scope.all.forEach(function(val) {
					val.isSelected = scope.isAllSelected;
				})
			});
			scope.$watch('all', function(newVal, oldVal) {
				if (oldVal) {
					oldVal.forEach(function(val) {
						val.isSelected = false;
					});
				}
				scope.isAllSelected = false;
			});
		}
	}
});
```

 Hello, I'm using TranslationsMixin:

```
class ProductItemSerializer(TranslationsMixin, WritableNestedModelSerializer):
      ...
     class Meta:
           model = Product
           translations = ProductTranslationSerializer(required=False)
           fields = (
                'id',
                ...
               'translation',
          ) 
```

But when I do PUT request to `/products/1/`
```
{
    "product_groups": {
         "id": 1
     }
}
```
I get error:

```
{
	"translations": [
		"This field is required."
	]
}
``` 
It's possible somehow set `required=False` to translations? Thank you.

I have an object with multiple levels of nested many=True serializers.

I simply can't figure out how to show this kind of an output in the swagger view. If I just reference the top-level serializer in YAML it doesn't seem to go more than 1 deep, and if I use the "type:" docstring I can't figure out how to show the nested arrays. What am I missing?

So, I want to end up with something like:
{  
    "publishers":[  
        {  
            "authors":[  
                {  
                    "books":[  
                        {  
                            "chapters":[  
                                {  
                                    "name":"chapter 1"
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

I'm writing a custom operator in c++. And I try to construct a NDArray object from a blob. I use NDArray because it is more dynamic and easier to use than mshadow::Tensor. However, I found that a NDAarray object constructed from an output blob hangs on call to WaitToWrite(). Is this a bug?

The code is as following:

  void Forward(const OpContext &ctx,
      const std::vector<TBlob> &in_data,
      const std::vector<OpReqType> &req,
      const std::vector<TBlob> &out_data,
      const std::vector<TBlob> &aux_args) override {
    CHECK(req[0] == kWriteTo);
    NDArray x(out_data[0], out_data[0].dev_id());
    x.WaitToWrite();  // hangs here
    ...
    x.SyncCopyFromCPU(...);  // which calls WaitToWrite() inside
}

cc1 some warnings treated as erros
command gcc failed exit status 1

saying

third_party/fermi-lite-0.1/mag.c:246:2: error: ISO C90 forbids mixed declarations and code [-Werror=declaration-after-statement]

in relation to

ku128_v *r = &g->v.a[idd>>1].nei[idd&1];

So will try editing and:
ku128_v *r;
r = &g->v.a[idd>>1].nei[idd&1];

Appears C90 std is fussy with this . Is C90 stipulation  necessary?

I am trying to change the Failover Record Type from Primary to Secondary and vice versa. I am not able to update from Console as it says, RRset for same type with Primary (or Sec) exists.

So thought of using boto3. However, getting Invalid Input. Could you please suggest what is missing here


> Current State:
> 
> test.example.com. is FAILOVER type record with test-us-west-2.example.com. as Primary and test-us-east-2.example.com. as secondary. 
> 
> Desired State:
> test-us-west-2.example.com became Secondary and test-us-east-2.example.com. become Primary
> 

```
import boto3
client = boto3.client("route53")
response = client.change_resource_record_sets(
        HostedZoneId='xxxxxxx',
	ChangeBatch={
	'Changes': [{
		'Action': 'UPSERT',
		'ResourceRecordSet': {
			'Failover': 'SECONDARY',
			'HealthCheckId': 'xx-xx-xx-xx-xxxxx',
			'Name': 'test.example.com.',
			'ResourceRecords': [{
				'Value': 'test-us-west-2.example.com.'
			}],
			'SetIdentifier': 'test-us-west-2.example.com.',
			'Type': 'CNAME'
		}
	}, {
		'Action': 'UPSERT',
		'ResourceRecordSet': {
			'Failover': 'PRIMARY',
			'HealthCheckId': 'xx-xx-xx-xx-xx',
			'Name': 'test.example.com.',
			'ResourceRecords': [{
				'Value': 'test-us-east-2.example.com.'
			}],
			'SetIdentifier': 'test-us-east-2.example.com.',
			'Type': 'CNAME'
		}
	}]
})
```

